Details.WorkoutDescription:
Pettit is an hour of aerobic Endurance work spent between 60-70% FTP.

Optional form drills include form sprints, speed-endurance intervals, and quadrant drills.
Details.GoalDescription:
Aerobic Endurance workouts are aimed at improving your aerobic-power-producing capabilities in a low stress manner.

By riding for increasingly longer periods of time, your endurance muscle fibers become more efficient at utilizing fat for fuel and sparing sugar stores for more intense efforts.

Additionally, Endurance workouts like this can improve oxygen delivery & utilization, increase muscular resistance to fatigue, improve integrity of connective tissue, and even help you improve your on-bike nutrition strategies.

Regarding the form drills, Pettit targets improvements in pedaling mechanics, leg speed, and sprinting form.

Alternates.WorkoutDescription:
Muir is 50 minutes of aerobic Endurance riding at a steady 70% FTP.

Optional drills include Speed Endurance intervals and some Cadence Spin-Ups.
Alternates.GoalDescription:
Improvements in aerobic endurance/aerobic base are the aim when working at moderate intensities well below lactate threshold. By sustaining this effort level for fairly long and sometimes quite long, minimally interrupted periods of time, your body will improve its aerobic capabilities thereby improving your level of power output at low to moderate levels of exertion - even though it still feels easy, you get faster.

Greater aerobic adaptation means you can further your ability to metabolize fat for energy before dipping into your far less sustainable sugar stores thereby preserving those stores for the higher-intensity efforts. This also means you'll require less food/carbohydrate to fuel your effort during your events.

Add in the optional speed drills and you'll also address muscular efficiency via the addition of speed work.

Try to maintain a cadence between 85-95rpm unless you choose to take part in the optional speed drills which can put your cadence well above 100rpm.

Alternates.WorkoutDescription: Homers Nose is an hour of mostly Endurance work between 55-75% FTP with recommendations to ride short segments around 120rpm, slightly longer segments around 70rpm, and the longest segments around 90rpm, should you choose to include the drills.
Alternates.GoalDescription:
Endurance training is primarily about furthering your aerobic capacity in the hopes of improving fat metabolism, energy delivery to the muscles, glycogen conservation in general, lower HR/higher aerobic power, improved neuromuscular efficiency, etc.

Shorter Endurance rides like this one done consistently can help time-constrained riders make up for some of that lack of pro rider time availability.

Follow along with the onscreen workout instructions or simply try to hold your spin within an 85-95rpm range.

Also consider spending some time adapting to and modifying your aero or climbing position & form while the workload is relatively low.

Alternates.WorkoutDescription: West Vidette is 45 minutes of aerobic Endurance riding ranging from 50-80% FTP.

By sustaining this effort level for fairly long and sometimes quite long, minimally interrupted periods of time, your body will improve its aerobic capabilities thereby improving your level of power output at low-to-moderate levels of exertion. 

Greater aerobic efficiency (your ability to better utilize oxygen to turn over ATP) means you can work harder before dipping into your far less sustainable sugar stores and preserve those stores for the higher-intensity efforts. This also means you'll require less food to fuel your effort during your events.

Try to maintain a cadence between 85-95rpm.

Alternates.WorkoutDescription:
Obelisk is 4x3-minute intervals of leg-speed drills at a very low 60% FTP with 3 minutes of rest between intervals.

Keep the pressure on the pedals light and your intensity low to moderate regardless of your cadence.
Alternates.GoalDescription:
Leg-speed drills are aimed at improving pedal economy during a light/recovery ride.

Focus on actively kicking over the top of the pedal stroke & pulling back across the bottom of the pedal stroke while remaining relaxed all with the intent of refining your pedaling technique, expending less energy at higher cadences & accumulating some extra, low-intensity mileage.

Beginning cadence should be above 90rpm, then simply spin more quickly until you've reached a spin between 110-120rpm without rocking or bouncing in the saddle.

Remain smooth & relaxed and hold this high rpm for the duration of the interval as long as you can maintain your form.

Alternates.WorkoutDescription:
The Recess rides range anywhere from 20-60 minutes in duration at roughly 50% FTP.

Exhausted rides, sometimes referred to as "accumulation rides" or "depleted rides" are performed within 4-24 hours after your last key workout, race/event, or any other similar, stressful ride.

These rides should leave you no more fatigued than you were before you hopped on your bike and there are no strict rules governing effort level as long as these feel recuperative and do not negatively impact your next key workout.
Alternates.GoalDescription: The goals behind the Recess rides are rather wide-ranging and include adaptations such as increased resistance to muscle damage, enhanced neuromuscular coordination (i.e. improved pedal economy), increased fat metabolism, and heat acclimation to name a few.

Alternates.WorkoutDescription:
Hoffman consists of 4 hours and 30 minutes of aerobic Endurance riding, most of which is spent between 60-70% FTP.

To pass the time and improve your pedal economy, Hoffman includes optional Form Sprints, Endurance Spinning intervals, Pistons/Kick & Pull pedaling drills as well as some Single-Leg Focus to keep you engaged over this long haul.
Alternates.GoalDescription:
Endurance workouts are aimed at improving your aerobic power production capabilities in a steady, low-stress manner. By training your endurance muscle fibers to better utilize oxygen to metabolize fat as fuel, your muscles can spare sugar stores for more intense efforts. This long/slow approach to fostering aerobic capabilities is the lighter, kinder alternative to high-intensity repeats, but both approaches target many of the same adaptations.

Unless otherwise noted, try to keep your spin above 85rpm, preferably above 95rpm.

Form Sprints: Practice high-rpm sprint simulations at low power outputs to reinforce proper sprinting technique by jumping out-of-the-saddle and winding up a light gear. As your cadence reaches its controllable peak, gracefully transition into the saddle where you can shift gears if necessary. These sprints are only 10s long and are all about leg speed, form, & technique. Experiment with which foot to lead with, and learn how to generate a lot of leg speed in very little time.

Endurance Spinning: Practice spinning slightly quicker than your natural, self-selected cadence. Ride at a cadence that's at the very top of your comfortable rpm range and remain there for a solid 5 minutes. The goal is to learn to turn the pedals more quickly with less force (muscle stress) thereby improving your ability to remain predominantly aerobic over a wide range of rpm's. If your HR rises more than a few BPM, you're pedaling too quickly - take it easy and stay relaxed but quick.

Pistons: Few if any riders need to practice pushing down on the pedals, but improvements in how well your knees move are both beneficial to economy and joint health. As you pedal, pay close attention to how your knees track. They should move directly up, directly down - like pistons - with little if any lateral movement, especially at the top of each pedalstroke. Focus on one knee for 30s before switching sides. 

Kick & Pull: A balanced pedalstroke is dependent upon consistent tension on your bike's drivetrain throughout the entire pedalstroke. Reinforce your ability to maintain tension through the weakest portions of the pedalstroke, the top & bottom quadrants. As your knee approaches top-dead-center, lightly kick your toes into the fronts of your shoes, and as your feet approach bottom-dead-center, lightly pull your heels into the backs of your shoes - kick & pull. Focus on just the kick for 30s, just the pull for 30s, then eventually both for 30s simultaneously.

Single-Leg Focus: The objective here is to learn to more effectively apply power through the entire pedalstroke by focusing strictly on one leg's activity through the bottom, upstroke, & over the top of the pedalstroke. For 90 seconds at a time, devote your attention to one leg before switching to the other. Your cadence may fall slightly, but these drills typically come more naturally to less experienced "one-leggers". Pay particular attention to lightly pulling your foot across the bottom, lifting your knee lightly upward & then softly kicking over the top of each pedalstroke. Add this drill indoors or outdoors as often as you like, more frequently if you recognize a substantial difference in one leg's strength or coordination.

As your cadence reaches its controllable peak, gracefully transition into the saddle where you can shift gears if necessary. Isolated Leg Training (One-Leggers): Like Single-Leg Focus drills, the objective here is to learn to more effectively apply power through the entire pedalstroke by focusing strictly on one leg's activity through the bottom, upstroke, and over the top of the pedalstroke. Completely unclip one foot from the pedal and rest it on your trainer, a stool, or anything that allows it to safely rest without interfering with your other leg's pedaling. Begin with slow cadence - very slow in some cases - and periods of 10-20s per leg unless you can pedal longer without "knocking" and don't worry about your temporarily low power, these drills aren't about strength. 

As you improve, your cadence will increase as will each leg's duration. Pay close attention your kick and pull thinking more in terms of horizontal/back and forth pedaling especially if you begin feeling deadspots in your pedalstroke or you begin hearing a knocking sound due to those deadspots. Keep tension on the chain and switch anytime your form degrades; don't practice bad habits just to tack on 5 or 10 more seconds. Include this drill indoors 2-3 times each week accumulating 5-10 minutes per leg each workout.

Form Sprints: Practice high-rpm sprint simulations at low power outputs to reinforce proper sprinting technique by jumping out-of-the-saddle and winding up a light gear. As your cadence reaches its controllable peak, gracefully transition into the saddle where you can shift gears if necessary. These sprints are only 10s long and are all about leg speed, form, and technique. Experiment with which foot to lead with, and learn how to generate a lot of leg speed in very little time.

Endurance Spinning: Practice spinning slightly quicker than your natural, self-selected cadence. Ride at a cadence that's at the very top of your comfortable rpm range and remain there for a solid 5 minutes. The goal is to learn to turn the pedals more quickly with less force (muscle stress) thereby improving your ability to remain predominantly aerobic over a wide range of rpm's. If your HR rises more than a few BPM, you're pedaling too quickly - take it easy and stay relaxed but quick.

Pistons: Few if any riders need to practice pushing down on the pedals, but improvements in how well your knees move are both beneficial to economy and joint health. Your cadence may fall slightly, but these drills typically come more naturally to less experienced "one-leggers". Pay particular attention to lightly pulling your foot across the bottom, lifting your knee lightly upward and then softly kicking over the top of each pedalstroke. Add this drill indoors or outdoors as often as you like, more frequently if you recognize a substantial difference in one leg's strength or coordination.

These rides should leave you no more fatigued than you were before you hopped on your bike and there are no strict rules governing effort level as long as these feel recuperative and do not negatively impact your next key workout.
Alternates.GoalDescription: The goals behind the Recess rides are rather wide-ranging and include adaptations such as increased resistance to muscle damage, enhanced neuromuscular coordination (i.e., improved pedal economy), increased fat metabolism, and even heat acclimation to name a few.

Alternates.WorkoutDescription: Cumberland -3 is a continuous 60-minute stretch of work between 70-75% FTP nestled inside of a 75-minute workout.
Alternates.GoalDescription:

This is where fairly conservative ultra-distance triathletes will live for hours at a time. This is also where a lot of time is spent during any long road ride or milder-terrain trail ride.

There is no scheduled rest during this workout, but brief, occasional backpedal breaks are encouraged if they're the difference between loss of form and a high-quality workout.

If appicable, use portions or entireties of these intervals to work on riding in your aerodynamic position without sacrificing power. Try to do so with a cadence above 85rpm, preferably above 90rpm.

Alternates.WorkoutDescription: Baxter -1 is 75 minutes of non-stop aerobic conditioning at 55-75% FTP where the effort changes based on cadence.
Alternates.GoalDescription:
Effectively a fixed-gear trainer ride with low to moderate effort levels, Baxter is aimed at improving your aerobic fitness by growing your body's ability to utilize fat for energy and spare sugar stores.

Additionally, you can improve your pedal efficiency through high-rpm spinning and also focus on furthering your muscular control and joint integrity via low-rpm grinding.

Cadence recommendations vary at least +/- 20rpm from your self-selected cadence.

So for example, if you typically ride at 90rpm then your rpm range will be 70-110rpm - the greater your capabilities, the greater this rpm range.

Improvements in aerobic endurance & efficiency are the aim when working at a moderate intensities well below lactate threshold. 

By sustaining this effort level during minimally interrupted periods of time, your body will improve its aerobic capabilities thereby improving your level of power output at low-to-moderate levels of exertion. 

Greater aerobic efficiency (your ability to better utilize oxygen to turn over ATP) means you can work harder before dipping into your far less sustainable sugar stores and preserve those stores for the higher-intensity efforts. This also means you'll require less food to fuel your effort during your events.

Try to keep your spin above 85rpm.

Alternates.WorkoutDescription: Haldimand consists of over 2 hours of aerobic Endurance riding spent between 40-55% FTP and includes 3x15-second sprints. It also includes some optional form sprints, endurance-spinning intervals, and some Isolated Leg Training (ILT) drills.
Alternates.GoalDescription:
Endurance workouts are aimed at improving your aerobic power production capabilities in a steady, low-stress manner. By training your endurance muscle fibers to better utilize oxygen to metabolize fat as fuel, your muscles can spare sugar stores for more intense efforts. This long/slow approach to fostering aerobic capabilities is the lighter, kinder alternative to high-intensity repeats, but both approaches target many of the same adaptations. 

The additional sprint efforts are aimed at increasing your ability to recruit additional muscle fibers in an effort to grow your work capacity and lift your sustainable power.

Try to keep your spin above 85rpm, well above 100rpm during the short sprints.

Endurance Spinning: Practice spinning slightly quicker than your natural, self-selected cadence.

Ride at a cadence that's at the very top of your comfortable rpm range and remain there for a solid 5 minutes. The goal is to learn to turn the pedals quicker with less force (muscle stress), thereby improving your ability to remain predominantly aerobic over a wide range of rpm. If your HR rises more than a few bpm, you're pedaling too quickly - take it easy and stay relaxed but quick.

Isolated Leg Training (One-Leggers): Like Single-Leg Focus drills, the objective here is to learn to more effectively apply power through the entire pedalstroke by focusing strictly on one leg's activity through the bottom, upstroke, & over the top of the pedalstroke.

Completely unclip one foot from the pedal and rest it on your trainer, a stool, or anything that allows it to safely rest without interfering with your other leg's pedaling. Begin with slow cadence - very slow in some cases - and periods of 10-20s per leg unless you can pedal longer without "knocking" and don't worry about your temporarily low power, these drills aren't about strength. As you improve, your cadence will increase as will each leg's duration.

Pay close attention to your kick & pull, thinking more in terms of horizontal/back & forth pedaling especially if you begin feeling deadspots in your pedalstroke or you begin hearing a knocking sound due to those deadspots. Keep tension on the chain and switch anytime your form degrades; don't practice bad habits just to tack on 5 or 10 more seconds. Include this drill indoors 2-3 times each week accumulating 5-10 minutes per leg each workout.

Form Sprints: Practice high-rpm sprint simulations at low power outputs to reinforce proper sprinting technique by jumping out-of-the-saddle and winding up a light gear.

As your cadence reaches its controllable peak, gracefully transition into the saddle where you can shift gears if necessary. These sprints are only 10s long and are all about leg speed, form, and technique. Experiment with which foot to lead with, and learn how to generate a lot of leg speed in very little time.

Alternates.WorkoutDescription: Apikuni is 2.5 hours of aerobic Endurance riding spent somewhere between 50-66% FTP.
Alternates.GoalDescription:
Aerobic Endurance training is primarily about cultivating a strong, wide aerobic base that includes all of the physiological adaptations inherent in long, steady, low-intensity riding, e.g., improved fat metabolism, glycogen conservation, lower HR/higher aerobic power, improved neuromuscular efficiency, etc.

Try to hold your spin between 85-95 rpm unless your specific cadence goals fall elsewhere.

Alternates.WorkoutDescription: Standing consists of nearly 90 minutes of aerobic Endurance riding spent between 50- 57% FTP.
Alternates.GoalDescription:
Aerobic Endurance workouts are aimed at improving your aerobic (oxygen-reliant) power producing capabilities in a low-stress manner.

By riding for increasingly longer periods of time, your endurance muscle fibers become more efficient at utilizing oxygen and sparing sugar stores for more intense efforts.

Additionally, Endurance workouts like this can improve oxygen delivery, increase muscular resistance to fatigue, improve integrity of connective tissue, and even help you improve your on-bike nutrition strategies.
